{"key":"processedPost-10123354","value":{"id":10123354,"first":10123181,"last":10123912,"when":1239133089,"utime":"04/07/09 10:38 PM","cleanedPost":"Using boiling water is the worst thing possible.&nbsp; The only reason it doesn't screw up the grow every single time is that coir is very hard for fungi spores to germinate on, thus it's probably the only substrate that's truly 'contaminant resistant'.<br />You're supposed to hydrate all bulk substrates with gently warm or even cold water, and then slowly bring the field capacity mixture up to 140F and maintain that temperature in the center of the substrate mix for an hour, without letting it exceed 160F during that hour.<br />Field capacity means when you grab a handful and squeeze hard, a few drops run out, but then stop after a second or two.<br />RR"}}